<p>

In <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../342/6248342.xml">
medieval</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../532/25532.xml">
Renaissance</link> depictions of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../284/55284.xml">
coats of arms</link>, the goutte was drawn with wavy sides (as shown above).  More modern depictions have smoothed the sides to make the droplets fatter and more symmetrical.</p>
<p>

In their earliest uses, gouttes were strewn upon the field of a coat of arms, a design called <b>goutty</b> or <b>gutty</b> (<language wordnetid="106282651" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../597/10597.xml">
French</link></language>
 <it>goutt√©e</it>).  It was only much later that the goutte came to be used individually in heraldry as a charge in its own right.</p>

